Adjust rack to middle and top positions and preheat oven to 400 degrees. Bring a
large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry all produce. Halve, peel, and
dice @yellow onion{1}; mince a few pieces until you have 2 TBSP (3 TBSP for 4
servings). Halve @fresh mozzarella{4%oz}; dice one half into four equal-sized pieces
(eight pieces for 4); tear remaining half into bite-size pieces.

In a #large bowl{}, soak half the @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup} (you'll use the rest
later) with @water{2%TBSP} (3 TBSP for 4 servings). Let sit until absorbed, then
add @ground beef{10%oz}, minced onion, half the @Tuscan Heat Spice{1/2%tbsp}
(you'll use the rest later), @salt{3/4%tsp} (1 1/2 tsp for 4), and
@black pepper{}. Mix to combine.

Lightly oil a #baking sheet{} with @vegetable oil{1%tsp}. Form beef mixture into
four 3-inch-wide rounds (eight rounds for 4); divide diced mozzarella between the
centers of each. Gently fold meat around cheese, shaping and sealing to create
cheese-stuffed meatballs. Place on prepared sheet. Bake on middle rack until
cooked through, ~{20-22%minutes}. Remove from oven; heat broiler to high or oven to
500 degrees.

Once water is boiling, add @cavatappi pasta{6%oz} to #pot{}. Cook until al dente,
~{9-11%minutes}. Drain and set aside. Reserve empty pot. Meanwhile, place
@butter{1%tbsp} in a #small microwave-safe bowl{}. Microwave until melted, about
~{30%seconds}. Stir in @Tuscan Heat Spice{1/4%tsp} (1/2 tsp for 4 servings; you'll
use the rest later), remaining @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, a large drizzle of
@olive oil{2%tsp}, @salt{}, and @black pepper{}.

Meanwhile, heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp} in a large, preferably
ovenproof, #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add diced onion; cook, stirring, until
softened, ~{4-6%minutes}. Stir in remaining @Tuscan Heat Spice{1/2%tbsp},
@crushed tomatoes{13.76%oz}, @tomato paste{1.5%oz}, @water{1/2%cup} (3/4 cup for 4
servings), @sugar{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4), and @salt{} until combined. Bring to a
simmer; cook until slightly thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in @butter{1%tbsp}
(2 TBSP for 4) until melted. Season generously with salt and pepper.

Carefully pour sauce into pot used for pasta; add cavatappi. If pasta seems dry,
add a splash of water. Gently stir in meatballs to coat. Carefully transfer
everything back into pan used for sauce.

> TIP: If your pan isn't ovenproof, transfer mixture to a 9-by-13-inch baking dish.

Top mixture with panko and @fresh mozzarella{remaining half}(torn). Broil or bake
on top rack until panko is golden brown and cheese is melted, ~{2-4%minutes}. Let
cool slightly, then serve.